snippet.title: "Project Muscle" - A finger touching invention 🤌🏻
snippet.description:
Every time you touch your phone screen, you are holding a piece of history that almost never made it to the world. Back in the 1960s, Corning developed a super-strong glass under a secret project called “Chemcor.” It was 700 times tougher than normal glass, created through a unique chemical strengthening process. Yet, there was no commercial demand for it, so it gathered dust on the shelves for decades.

Fast forward to 2005, when Steve Jobs was building the first iPhone. Frustrated with plastic screens getting scratched, he demanded a tough, scratch-resistant glass. Apple turned to Corning, who revived their forgotten invention, refined it, and rebranded it as Gorilla Glass. In 2007, the iPhone launch showcased this revolutionary screen, forcing the entire smartphone industry to adopt it. Today, Gorilla Glass protects billions of devices worldwide, all thanks to a 40-year-old invention Steve Jobs refused to ignore.

snippet.title: Phones Spy on You Even When They’re OFF | Imtinan Ahmad
snippet.description:
Have you ever wondered why phone companies suddenly removed replaceable batteries and forced us into built-in ones? 🤔 From 2014 onwards, almost every smartphone brand followed Apple’s lead and many believe it wasn’t just for “design” or “slimness.”

Edward Snowden’s leaks revealed shocking truths: 📱

Your phone can still track your location even when it’s turned OFF.

The mic and camera can be remotely activated.

Even alarms work on a powered-off phone proving it’s never really off.

This video uncovers the hidden story of surveillance, 24/7 tracking, and why agencies wanted full control. Maybe your phone, smart TV, or even your fridge is spying on you…

⚠️ The European Union plans to bring back replaceable batteries by 2027, but is it already too late?

Remember the world may watch you, but Allah ﷻ is always watching them too.

#surveillance  #smartphones #foryou #facts
